cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.MM, cs.COM 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper discusses the concept of distributed MIMO precoding and derives the multiplexing gain as a function of the scaling in the SNR, which are topics related to information theory. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper discusses the joint precoding across two distant transmitters and two receivers, which are topics related to networking and internet architecture. 
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper discusses the distributed channel state information configuration where each transmitter has its own local estimate of the channel and no communication is possible between the transmitters, which are topics related to social and information networks. 
4. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The paper discusses the performance of different precoding schemes in terms of signal-to-noise ratio, which is a topic related to multimedia. 
5. cs.COM (Computational Complexity) - The paper does not directly discuss computational complexity, but it does involve the design of optimal precoding schemes, which may have computational complexity implications.
